103
00:07:23,286 --> 00:07:25,786
Is that right?

104
00:07:29,186 --> 00:07:33,186
The cruiser that M is on board sailed under Minato Bridge just now.

105
00:07:33,186 --> 00:07:36,086
The culprit's planning to get the money somewhere along the river.

106
00:07:36,086 --> 00:07:37,286
Keep your eyes open.

107
00:07:37,286 --> 00:07:38,286
Roger.

108
00:07:40,086 --> 00:07:42,286
The waves of the transceiver

109
00:07:42,286 --> 00:07:43,886
works only in a range of at most, 100 meters.

110
00:07:43,886 --> 00:07:46,586
The culprit should be somewhere in this range.

111
00:07:46,586 --> 00:07:48,786
Sato, where are you now?

112
00:07:48,786 --> 00:07:51,486
We're waiting right across Eitai River.

113
00:07:51,486 --> 00:07:53,486
We confirmed with the cruiser company

114
00:07:53,486 --> 00:07:57,386
and found that it's supposed to go from Sumida River to Ooyoko River.

115
00:07:57,386 --> 00:08:00,686
You two go on ahead to Ooyoko River.

116
00:08:00,686 --> 00:08:01,686
Roger.

117
00:08:04,386 --> 00:08:05,686
Wow. How wonderful.

118
00:08:05,686 --> 00:08:07,186
Amazing.

119
00:08:10,586 --> 00:08:13,586
It's about time you start working for me.

120
00:08:13,586 --> 00:08:16,686
That cruiser is headed for Oojima water gate

121
00:08:16,686 --> 00:08:18,486
and will be going into Ooyoko River.

122
00:08:18,486 --> 00:08:22,986
Then, put the briefcase on the roof of the cruiser.

123
00:08:22,986 --> 00:08:25,386
Put it in the center so that it doesn't fall.

124
00:08:25,386 --> 00:08:28,586
Then, go back to your seat and wait for the next contact.

125
00:08:38,386 --> 00:08:40,186
It's not rolling anymore.

126
00:08:40,186 --> 00:08:43,186
Ooyoko River is a canal, that's why.

127
00:08:43,186 --> 00:08:46,486
A local feudal lord made this by order of the Edo Shogunate.

128
00:08:52,586 --> 00:08:53,786
Amazing.

129
00:08:57,286 --> 00:08:58,786
That brat...

130
00:09:00,486 --> 00:09:01,886
Don't you get in my way, brat!

131
00:09:01,886 --> 00:09:03,286
Lower your head!

132
00:09:06,886 --> 00:09:07,886
That was close!

133
00:09:08,886 --> 00:09:11,786
During high tide, water level rises, that the bridge gets so low,

134
00:09:11,786 --> 00:09:14,886
we can't go under it even on this cruiser.

135
00:09:14,886 --> 00:09:16,386
I see.

136
00:09:16,386 --> 00:09:18,386
Well, I guess you don't bow so often or lower your head really low

137
00:09:18,386 --> 00:09:21,086
and turn it into a good experience while you're at it.

138
00:09:21,086 --> 00:09:22,086
What did you say?

139
00:09:23,086 --> 00:09:25,586
The briefcase is on the roof.

140
00:09:39,886 --> 00:09:41,286
It's impossible to pull the briefcase

141
00:09:41,286 --> 00:09:43,686
up from the bridge in this crowd people.

142
00:09:43,686 --> 00:09:44,886
Besides...

143
00:09:48,886 --> 00:09:52,386
With so many surveillance cameras all over the place, the more so.

144
00:10:10,086 --> 00:10:11,386
Did you wait long?

145
00:10:15,086 --> 00:10:16,086
That was close.

146
00:10:43,586 --> 00:10:45,686
M has entered Heikyu River.

147
00:10:46,786 --> 00:10:49,686
The briefcase is on the roof of the cruiser.

148
00:10:49,686 --> 00:10:52,186
What? Keep your eyes on the cruiser!

149
00:10:52,186 --> 00:10:53,286
Roger!

150
00:10:53,286 --> 00:10:54,786
I'll go get the car.

151
00:11:34,286 --> 00:11:36,286
The briefcase is gone!

152
00:11:43,301 --> 00:11:45,301
The briefcase is gone!

153
00:11:47,301 --> 00:11:49,501
Conan? What brings you here?

154
00:11:49,501 --> 00:11:51,001
The briefcase is gone!

155
00:11:51,001 --> 00:11:52,301
-What? -What?

156
00:11:52,301 --> 00:11:54,601
Bad news! We've got to contact the inspector.

157
00:11:57,801 --> 00:11:58,801
Darn!

158
00:12:00,101 --> 00:12:01,601
Pops!

159
00:12:01,601 --> 00:12:04,401
Pops! We've got trouble!

160
00:12:04,401 --> 00:12:06,201
Shut up! Don't bother me!

161
00:12:06,201 --> 00:12:08,801
The briefcase on the roof is gone!

162
00:12:08,801 --> 00:12:09,801
What?

163
00:12:12,901 --> 00:12:15,601
It's gone! It's gone! It's gone! It's gone!

164
00:12:15,601 --> 00:12:18,001
Hey, look out, sir!

165
00:12:18,001 --> 00:12:21,201
The briefcase is gone!

166
00:12:24,901 --> 00:12:26,001
Mr. Mouri!

167
00:12:27,701 --> 00:12:29,601
How'd he do it?

168
00:12:29,601 --> 00:12:33,801
How on earth the culprit take the briefcase?

169
00:12:39,901 --> 00:12:42,401
"Mouri Detective Agency"

170
00:12:44,101 --> 00:12:45,101
In other words,

171
00:12:45,101 --> 00:12:47,901
you got instructions over the transceiver?

172
00:12:47,901 --> 00:12:51,501
To put the briefcase on the roof after entering Ooyoko River?

173
00:12:51,501 --> 00:12:52,501
Yes...

174
00:12:55,601 --> 00:12:56,601
Yes.

175
00:12:56,601 --> 00:12:59,001
You got nothing, no directions, after that?

176
00:12:59,001 --> 00:13:00,001
No.

177
00:13:02,001 --> 00:13:06,301
And, by the time you realized it, the briefcase was gone?

178
00:13:06,301 --> 00:13:09,301
Yes, sir. Because he told me to go back to my seat

179
00:13:09,301 --> 00:13:11,401
and wait for further contact.

180
00:13:11,401 --> 00:13:12,801
What a shame.

181
00:13:12,801 --> 00:13:14,401
And, Conan...

182
00:13:14,401 --> 00:13:17,501
When did you last see the briefcase?

183
00:13:17,501 --> 00:13:19,101
Well...

184
00:13:19,101 --> 00:13:22,101
Over here. Totomi Bridge here.

185
00:13:22,101 --> 00:13:26,801
The last we saw of it was Shiomi Bridge here.

186
00:13:26,801 --> 00:13:32,501
And you realized that the briefcase was gone at Hamazono Bridge here.

187
00:13:32,501 --> 00:13:37,001
In other words, the culprit would have had to take the briefcase

188
00:13:37,001 --> 00:13:39,701
from somewhere between Heikyu Bridge and Hamazono Bridge.

189
00:13:39,701 --> 00:13:42,801
Mr. Mouri, was there anything you noticed?

190
00:13:44,901 --> 00:13:47,301
I'm very sorry.

191
00:13:47,301 --> 00:13:49,801
It seems like I've caught a cold

192
00:13:49,801 --> 00:13:51,901
That's obvious.

193
00:13:51,901 --> 00:13:53,001
Oh, right.

194
00:13:53,001 --> 00:13:56,901
Bback then, I heard a metallic sound of something banging onto steel.

195
00:13:56,901 --> 00:13:59,201
A metallic sound?

196
00:13:59,201 --> 00:14:03,001
If I remember correctly, somewhere around here...

197
00:14:03,001 --> 00:14:05,601
I think it was a small bridge.

198
00:14:05,601 --> 00:14:09,401
There were two small boats anchored under the bridge.

199
00:14:09,401 --> 00:14:11,301
Were there people on the boats?

200
00:14:11,301 --> 00:14:13,401
No, no one.

201
00:14:13,401 --> 00:14:16,701
I heard the sound when the skipper veered the cruiser to the right

202
00:14:16,701 --> 00:14:19,301
to avoid the boats and sailed under the bridge

203
00:14:20,601 --> 00:14:22,001
What was that?

204
00:14:22,001 --> 00:14:23,801
Maybe we hit a bridge?

205
00:14:23,801 --> 00:14:25,201
No way.

206
00:14:25,201 --> 00:14:27,401
If so the cruiser should sway more.

207
00:14:27,401 --> 00:14:29,001
I see.

208
00:14:30,001 --> 00:14:32,501
That was probably Shigure Bridge.

209
00:14:32,501 --> 00:14:35,401
When we were watching from Shiomi Bridge,

210
00:14:35,401 --> 00:14:37,801
Heikyu Bridge was in sight,

211
00:14:37,801 --> 00:14:39,701
but there were no boats.

212
00:14:39,701 --> 00:14:43,101
Besides, Ishihama Bridge just ahead of Shigure Bridge

213
00:14:43,101 --> 00:14:45,301
has a water gate right behind it.

214
00:14:45,301 --> 00:14:49,001
I don't think you'll get the impression of it being a small bridge.

215
00:14:49,001 --> 00:14:50,501
I see.

216
00:14:50,501 --> 00:14:53,101
The next bridge is already Hamazono Bridge

217
00:14:53,101 --> 00:14:55,001
so I'm sure that there's no doubt that the metallic sound

218
00:14:55,001 --> 00:14:58,001
was heard at Shigure Bridge.

219
00:14:58,001 --> 00:15:00,801
But, I wonder if that metallic sound

220
00:15:00,801 --> 00:15:03,101
has anything to do with the case we're dealing with now?

221
00:15:03,101 --> 00:15:05,101
Inspector Megure.

222
00:15:05,101 --> 00:15:08,501
This was found near the water of Heikyu Bridge.

223
00:15:09,701 --> 00:15:10,901
That's...

224
00:15:13,101 --> 00:15:14,401
Mr. Mouri,

225
00:15:14,401 --> 00:15:17,101
is this the briefcase?

226
00:15:18,101 --> 00:15:19,901
No mistake, that's it!

227
00:15:19,901 --> 00:15:22,701
Open it and confirm the inside too.

228
00:15:22,701 --> 00:15:24,301
May take a look?

229
00:15:31,801 --> 00:15:36,901
Pops, the cloth of the lid of the briefcase is ripped.

230
00:15:36,901 --> 00:15:38,101
What?

231
00:15:39,101 --> 00:15:40,601
According to forensics,

232
00:15:40,601 --> 00:15:42,001
just as Conan has mentioned,

233
00:15:42,001 --> 00:15:44,001
the inside of the lid has been ripped off,

234
00:15:44,001 --> 00:15:45,401
and further inside,

235
00:15:45,401 --> 00:15:48,801
there seems to be a trace of something having been rigged onto it.

236
00:15:48,801 --> 00:15:49,801
What?

237
00:15:49,801 --> 00:15:52,301
Then, does that mean that the culprit used whatever it was

238
00:15:52,301 --> 00:15:54,501
that was rigged on to it, to take the briefcase?

239
00:15:54,501 --> 00:15:57,701
No, we don't know that yet...

240
00:16:00,101 --> 00:16:01,501
Mr. Mouri?

241
00:16:01,501 --> 00:16:02,901
Dad.

242
00:16:02,901 --> 00:16:04,101
Inspector.

243
00:16:04,101 --> 00:16:07,601
I've figured out how the culprit had taken the briefcase.

244
00:16:07,601 --> 00:16:08,701
Mouri.

245
00:16:08,701 --> 00:16:11,001
He's not nasal anymore?

246
00:16:11,001 --> 00:16:12,201
Rats.

247
00:16:12,201 --> 00:16:15,101
It flashed upon me, that my nose suddenly unplugged.

248
00:16:16,401 --> 00:16:18,801
Never mind that, but inspector...

249
00:16:18,801 --> 00:16:21,701
The culprit probably used a strong magnet.

250
00:16:21,701 --> 00:16:23,401
Magnet?

251
00:16:23,401 --> 00:16:25,201
The characteristic of Ooyoko River

252
00:16:25,201 --> 00:16:28,301
is that the water level greatly changes during high and low tide.

253
00:16:28,301 --> 00:16:31,701
The distance between the bridge becomes very narrow.

254
00:16:31,701 --> 00:16:33,501
The culprit probably checked the time

255
00:16:33,501 --> 00:16:37,101
that the water level rises beforehand

256
00:16:37,101 --> 00:16:41,601
and rigged a strong magnet onto the lid of the briefcase.

257
00:16:41,601 --> 00:16:43,801
By doing so, when the cruiser sails

258
00:16:43,801 --> 00:16:46,101
under the extremely narrow space of the bridge...

259
00:16:47,801 --> 00:16:49,401
Wait a minute.

260
00:16:49,401 --> 00:16:51,101
There are many bridges,

261
00:16:51,101 --> 00:16:53,301
so there's no way of telling which bridge it would attach too, no?

262
00:16:53,301 --> 00:16:59,101
No. So the culprit used an electromagnet

263
00:16:59,101 --> 00:17:01,201
that would generates magnetic force at his convenience.

264
00:17:02,801 --> 00:17:05,701
The electromagnet that is made by wrapping

265
00:17:05,701 --> 00:17:08,001
a coil around a magnetic material generates magnetic force

266
00:17:08,001 --> 00:17:10,301
only when electric current is applied to the coil.

267
00:17:10,301 --> 00:17:13,501
The culprit probably embedded in the lid of the briefcase

268
00:17:13,501 --> 00:17:16,101
an iron bar wrapped with coil and a battery.

269
00:17:16,101 --> 00:17:20,801
Then, he installed a remote control switch that enables remote operation.

270
00:17:43,001 --> 00:17:45,601
Finally, after everyone left,

271
00:17:45,601 --> 00:17:48,301
he switched off the power and retrieved the briefcase.

272
00:17:51,201 --> 00:17:54,401
Okay! Based on Mouri's deduction,

273
00:17:54,401 --> 00:17:58,001
re-investigate the vicinity of Ooyoko River and Heikyu River.

274
00:17:58,001 --> 00:17:59,101
-Yes, sir. -Yes sir.

275
00:18:02,101 --> 00:18:03,901
Geez, dad...

276
00:18:03,901 --> 00:18:07,601
Your cold will get worse if you sleep in a place like this.

277
00:18:07,601 --> 00:18:11,601
I wonder why the culprit designated pops?

278
00:18:11,601 --> 00:18:13,101
I wonder...

279
00:18:13,101 --> 00:18:16,801
The papers of the cases that pops handled are still here, aren't they?

280
00:18:16,801 --> 00:18:19,801
Yeah, I think they're filed.

281
00:18:19,801 --> 00:18:22,901
Maybe we'll be able to figure something out by looking at those files.

282
00:18:25,001 --> 00:18:30,301
Maybe that culprit is somebody who has a grudge against dad?

283
00:18:32,101 --> 00:18:33,701
Could be.

284
00:18:44,801 --> 00:18:48,701
Is anything wrong, Ran?

285
00:18:48,701 --> 00:18:51,001
No, it's nothing.

286
00:18:52,701 --> 00:18:54,401
I was just thinking that if it were Shinichi,

287
00:18:54,401 --> 00:18:57,301
he would immediately solve a problem like this.

288
00:18:59,201 --> 00:19:00,801
Don't worry.

289
00:19:00,801 --> 00:19:02,901
I'll solve it for you.

290
00:19:04,301 --> 00:19:06,601
Just as would be expected of a member of the Youth Detective Squad.

291
00:19:06,601 --> 00:19:09,901
Then, shall we solve it, the two of us, in place of dad?

292
00:19:09,901 --> 00:19:10,901
Yes.

293
00:19:12,101 --> 00:19:14,801
The keyword is New Image.

294
00:19:14,801 --> 00:19:18,701
I'm sure that it has something to do with New Image and pops.

295
00:20:19,701 --> 00:20:23,601
"Mouri Detective Agency"

296
00:20:39,801 --> 00:20:41,001
I found it.

297
00:20:41,001 --> 00:20:43,601
Isn't this it?

298
00:20:43,601 --> 00:20:45,301
This.

299
00:20:45,301 --> 00:20:48,101
Satoshi Nishizawa, 32 years old.

300
00:20:48,101 --> 00:20:53,001
Mechanic engineer for New Image, an import car dealer.

301
00:20:53,001 --> 00:20:56,701
There is a request from Kaori Ida, 37 years old,

302
00:20:56,701 --> 00:21:00,201
to find the person who has been stalking her.

303
00:21:00,201 --> 00:21:01,601
As a result of the investigation,

304
00:21:01,601 --> 00:21:03,601
it becomes apparent that the stalker is Nishizawa.

305
00:21:03,601 --> 00:21:06,901
There was a court order prohibiting him from going close to her.

306
00:21:06,901 --> 00:21:10,101
Thus, he was fired.

307
00:21:10,101 --> 00:21:12,601
This is a case of 2 months ago.

308
00:21:12,601 --> 00:21:13,801
What's his address?

309
00:21:13,801 --> 00:21:15,801
Fukagawa, Koto ward.

310
00:21:15,801 --> 00:21:17,701
Isn't this near Ooyoko River?

311
00:21:17,701 --> 00:21:18,701
Yes.

312
00:22:53,101 --> 00:22:54,101
This way.

313
00:22:58,701 --> 00:23:00,501
It's that apartment, isn't it?

314
00:23:00,501 --> 00:23:01,501
Yes.

315
00:23:06,201 --> 00:23:09,501
Mr. Nishizawa. Are you in?

316
00:23:09,501 --> 00:23:11,101
Mr. Nishizawa!

317
00:23:14,101 --> 00:23:15,701
It seems he's not in.

318
00:23:15,701 --> 00:23:16,701
Yes.

319
00:23:20,001 --> 00:23:21,101
It's open.

320
00:23:24,401 --> 00:23:27,201
Mr. Nishizawa, aren't you home?

321
00:23:28,301 --> 00:23:30,001
Mr. Nishizawa!

322
00:23:34,601 --> 00:23:35,801
Conan.

323
00:23:44,901 --> 00:23:46,901
No, Conan.

324
00:23:46,901 --> 00:23:49,201
You shouldn't go into other people's houses without permission.

325
00:24:01,860 --> 00:24:03,620
Next Conan's Hint:

326
00:24:03,800 --> 00:24:05,760
"Flower viewing boat".

327
00:24:06,060 --> 00:24:07,900
Dad, are you okay?

328
00:24:08,500 --> 00:24:56,001
I guess he'd like to run to see cherry blossoms, but the only thing that's running is his nose.

